IFA Hotels, Howden Africa, Massmart: South Africa Stock Preview

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-03-22T06:44:56Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-21/ifa-hotels-howden-africa-primeserv-south-african-stock-market-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or
fall in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last close.  South  Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index snapped two
days of gains, declining 41.47, or 0.1 percent, to 30,677.08 at
the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg March 18. The country’s markets
were closed yesterday for a public holiday.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI SJ): Africa’s second-biggest gold
producer is seeking to buy the remaining shares in its Peruvian
subsidiary that it doesn’t already own. Gold Fields declined 65
cents, or 0.6 percent, to 115 rand.  Howden Africa Holdings Ltd. (HWN)  : The maker of
equipment to handle air, gas and liquids reported a 31 percent
decline in per share earnings, to 1.0552 rand in the year ended
December, from 1.5248 rand a year earlier, according to a
statement released by the company after the close of trading on
March 18. The shares gained 20 cents, or 1.9 percent, to 11
rand.  IFA Hotels & Resorts Ltd. (IFH)  : The gaming and leisure
company said after the close of trading March 18 it would report
earnings per share of between 1 cent and 3 cents in the first
half through December, compared with a loss of 10.41 cents a
share a year earlier, according to a trading update filed on the
stock exchange. The stock was unchanged at 57 cents.  Massmart Holdings Ltd. (MSM)  (MSM SJ ): South Africa’s
Competition Tribunal said it received an application from
government departments to postpone a hearing today over  Wal-Mart
Stores Inc. (WMT) ’s plan to take control of Massmart Holdings Ltd.
Massmart fell 49 cents, or 0.4 percent, to 133.71 rand.  Pretoria Portland Cement Co. (PPC SJ): Africa’s largest
cement producer said its first-half “financial results” will
fall by more than 30 percent. PPC climbed 63 cents, or 2.5
percent, to 25.97 rand.  Primeserv Group Ltd. (PMV)  : The investment holding
company whose units manage skills-training centers said in an 
update after the close of March 18 trading that it expects to
report a decline of between 25 and 35 percent in earnings per
share in the year ended December. Primeserv was unchanged at 37
cents.  Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) gained 1.5 percent to $24.88.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) rose 1.7 percent to $45.01. BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) increased 0.9 percent to $75.27. DRDGold
Ltd. (DROOY US) fell 2.8 percent to $4.60.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)   advanced 2.4 percent to $16.81. Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HMY
US) jumped 4.1 percent to $12.36. Impala Platinum Holdings
(IMPUY US) rose 3 percent to $27.35. Sappi Ltd. (SPP US)
advanced 1.5 percent to $4.81. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) gained 2.7
percent to $53.32.  To contact the reporter on this story:
